{
    "analysis": "The metric-level scan found pervasive, sustained anomalies (31/31 minutes) concentrated in container memory-related KPIs, primarily on node-6 (many recommendationservice/paymentservice/adservice pods) and some on node-5 (shippingservice). Earliest anomalies for the top pairs start at 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00 and persist across the 02:00–02:30 window. This suggests memory pressure or memory-failure behavior on specific nodes/pods. To localize root cause(s) and separate two distinct failures, we need to (A) collapse KPI-level anomalies to pod/service/node-level summaries to find which components exhibit broad multi-KPI faults and their first-failure times, and (B) use traces to determine downstream faulty components in call chains if multiple pods of a service are flagged. Logs can then be consulted for reason (e.g., memory OOM, GC, memory_failures). Next we should produce a compact per-component anomaly summary to identify the most affected pods/services/nodes and earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric-level anomaly aggregates already computed in kernel (the table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, global_P5, points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window), produce a compact per-cmdb_id summary as follows:\n1) For each cmdb_id compute: num_kpis_scanned (count of kpi_name rows), num_kpis_with_any_anomaly (count where anomaly_count>0), earliest_anomaly_ts_across_kpis (min of earliest_anomaly_ts where anomaly_count>0), max_severity = max over kpis of absolute deviation defined as max(|max_value_in_window - global_P95|, |min_value_in_window - global_P5|).\n2) Also derive service_name by stripping the trailing \"-<number>\" from cmdb_id for pod-like names (e.g., recommendationservice-2 -> recommendationservice); if cmdb_id matches node-<n> leave service_name as node-<n>.\n3) Return the top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by num_kpis_with_any_anomaly desc, then by max_severity desc. Include columns: cmdb_id, service_name, num_kpis_scanned, num_kpis_with_any_anomaly, earliest_anomaly_ts_across_kpis, max_severity. Also return the total number of distinct cmdb_id scanned.\nKeep output compact and limited to these aggregates (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global-threshold calculation and windowed anomaly detection across metrics and traces. Metric analysis shows pervasive, sustained memory-related anomalies beginning at 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00, concentrated on node-6 (34 distinct cmdb_ids affected) and to a lesser degree node-5 (6 cmdb_ids). Many container_memory_* KPIs and container_memory_failures are non-zero for entire window, suggesting memory pressure or allocation failures. Trace analysis is noisy because many trace P95/P5 are zero; traces are not yet decisive. To determine the two failures precisely we need the earliest concrete memory-failure events (container_memory_failures > 0) per pod and per node within the window to decide whether these are node-level failures (many pods simultaneously impacted) or isolated container failures. The next step is to extract the memory_failure metric events (value>0) during the incident window and summarize earliest timestamps per pod and associated node (from the kpi_name). This will let us identify exact root cause occurrence times and whether node-6 and node-5 correspond to distinct failures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv: filter rows where kpi_name (case-insensitive) contains 'memory_fail' OR 'memory.fail' OR 'memory_failures' and value > 0, and timestamp is between 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21 02:30:00+08:00 inclusive. For each distinct cmdb_id produce: earliest_timestamp_with_value_gt0 (min), count_of_points_with_value_gt0, max_value_in_window. Also attempt to extract the node id by searching the kpi_name text for substring 'node-<N>' (if present) and include that as a column. Return the top 50 rows sorted by count_of_points_with_value_gt0 desc then earliest_timestamp asc. Also return a small node-level summary: for each node found, the number_of_distinct_cmdb_ids_with_memory_failures and the node-level earliest timestamp (min across its pods). Keep outputs compact and limited to these aggregates (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have run global-threshold calculations and windowed anomaly detection across metrics and traces. Metric analysis shows widespread, sustained memory-related anomalies starting at 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00, concentrated on node-6 (majority of affected pods) and also present on node-5. Memory-failure metrics (container_memory_failures or similarly named KPIs) with value>0 occur on many pods (27 distinct cmdb_ids), with node-6 showing 21 pods affected and node-5 showing 6. The earliest memory-related anomalies (and many other KPI anomalies) begin at 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00. To determine the two failures precisely we need to confirm, per node, the exact first memory_failure event time and which pods exhibited that first event (to decide whether failures are node-level or isolated container-level). This will let us attribute each failure to either node-6 or node-5 (or other nodes) and assign the precise occurrence datetime and reason (memory failures).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the metric-level records where kpi_name contains 'memory_fail' or 'memory_failures' (case-insensitive) and value > 0 within the time window 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 02:30:00+08:00, produce a compact node-level summary: for each node (extract node id from kpi_name by substring 'node-<N>') return: node_id, node_earliest_memory_failure_ts (the minimum timestamp where any pod on that node had value>0), list_of_cmdb_ids_with_event_at_node_earliest_ts (limit to first 10 names), and total_distinct_cmdb_ids_with_memory_failures_on_node. Limit output to all nodes found (expected node-6 and node-5). Keep output compact and bounded (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric and trace anomaly scans. Metrics show widespread, sustained memory-related anomalies and explicit memory-failure events (container_memory_failures or similar) beginning at 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00. Node-level extraction shows node-6 (21 pods) and node-5 (6 pods) both have earliest memory-failure events at 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00. This strongly suggests two separate failures: one centered on node-6 and another on node-5, both starting at the start of the 02:00 window, with underlying reason being memory failures/pressure on those nodes. To further confirm the reason and rule out alternative causes (process termination, OOM logs, or other resource issues), we need to examine application logs for the affected pods during the window to see evidence (e.g., OOM kills, GC/heap logs, container restarts, error_count spikes). error_logs.csv is empty so focus on log.csv entries for the affected cmdb_ids. The next step is to retrieve bounded aggregates from log.csv for the cmdb_ids showing memory failures to look for error_count or other anomalies that corroborate memory failure/terminations.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From log.csv filter rows to timestamps between 2022-03-21 02:00:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21 02:30:00+08:00 inclusive and cmdb_id in the list of cmdb_ids with memory-failures (the 27 cmdb_ids previously identified). For each cmdb_id produce: total_log_rows_in_window, max_log_error_count (max of log.error_count if present else NA), sum_log_error_count, max_log_row_count (max of log.row_count if present else NA), earliest_ts_where_log_error_count_gt0 (if any). Return a compact table of the top 20 cmdb_ids sorted by max_log_error_count desc then total_log_rows desc. Also return up to 10 sample raw log rows (ts, cmdb_id, log_name, value) where log.error_count > 0, limited to first 10 matches. Keep outputs compact and bounded (no full raw series)."
}

